1
00:01:37,263 --> 00:01:41,393
<i>My father's name was John Kinsella.</i>
<i>It's an Irish name.</i>

2
00:01:42,018 --> 00:01:44,270
<i>He was born in North Dakota in 1896...</i>

3
00:01:44,396 --> 00:01:45,939
<i>...and never saw a big city...</i>

4
00:01:46,064 --> 00:01:49,317
<i>...until he came back from France in 1918.</i>

5
00:01:49,984 --> 00:01:53,863
<i>He settled in Chicago, where he learned</i>
<i>to live and die with the White Sox.</i>

6
00:01:54,364 --> 00:01:57,283
<i>Died a little</i>
<i>when they lost the 1919 World Series...</i>

7
00:01:57,992 --> 00:02:00,745
<i>...died a lot the following summer</i>
<i>when eight teammates...</i>

8
00:02:00,870 --> 00:02:03,123
<i>...were accused of throwing that Series.</i>

9
00:02:03,456 --> 00:02:06,710
<i>He played some in the minors,</i>
<i>but nothing came of it.</i>

10
00:02:07,293 --> 00:02:09,212
<i>Moved to Brooklyn in '35...</i>

11
00:02:09,546 --> 00:02:11,548
<i>...married Mom in '38...</i>

12
00:02:11,673 --> 00:02:14,175
<i>...was already an old man</i>
<i>at the naval yards...</i>

13
00:02:14,384 --> 00:02:16,386
<i>...when I was born in 1952.</i>

14
00:02:17,345 --> 00:02:19,222
<i>My name's Ray Kinsella.</i>

15
00:02:19,597 --> 00:02:24,060
<i>Mom died when I was 3,</i>
<i>and I suppose Dad did the best he could.</i>

16
00:02:24,352 --> 00:02:29,482
<i>Instead of Mother Goose, I was put to bed</i>
<i>to stories of Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig...</i>

17
00:02:29,607 --> 00:02:32,152
<i>...and the great Shoeless Joe Jackson.</i>

18
00:02:32,777 --> 00:02:36,489
<i>Dad was a Yankees fan then,</i>
<i>so I rooted for Brooklyn.</i>

19
00:02:36,614 --> 00:02:41,327
<i>But in '58, the Dodgers moved away,</i>
<i>so we had to find other reasons to fight.</i>

20
00:02:41,536 --> 00:02:42,579
<i>We did.</i>

21
00:02:42,787 --> 00:02:44,789
<i>When it came time to go to college...</i>

22
00:02:44,914 --> 00:02:47,292
<i>...I picked the farthest</i>
<i>from home I could find.</i>

23
00:02:48,793 --> 00:02:52,672
<i>This drove him up the wall,</i>
<i>which, I suppose, was the point.</i>

24
00:02:53,256 --> 00:02:57,302
<i>Officially my major was English,</i>
<i>but really it was the '60s.</i>

25
00:02:57,802 --> 00:03:00,180
<i>I marched, I smoked some grass...</i>

26
00:03:00,472 --> 00:03:03,850
<i>...I tried to like sitar music,</i>
<i>and I met Annie.</i>

27
00:03:04,726 --> 00:03:08,104
<i>The only thing we had in common</i>
<i>was that she came from Iowa...</i>

28
00:03:08,229 --> 00:03:10,065
<i>...and I'd once heard of Iowa.</i>

29
00:03:11,107 --> 00:03:13,318
<i>After graduation,</i>
<i>we moved to the Midwest...</i>

30
00:03:13,443 --> 00:03:16,112
<i>...and stayed with her family</i>
<i>as long as we could.</i>

31
00:03:16,237 --> 00:03:18,156
<i>Almost a full afternoon.</i>

32
00:03:19,115 --> 00:03:21,910
<i>Annie and I got married in June of '74.</i>

33
00:03:22,285 --> 00:03:24,120
<i>Dad died that fall.</i>

34
00:03:24,788 --> 00:03:27,082
<i>A few years later, Karin was born.</i>

35
00:03:27,207 --> 00:03:29,376
<i>She smelled weird,</i>
<i>but we loved her anyway.</i>

36
00:03:30,085 --> 00:03:33,963
<i>Then Annie got the crazy idea</i>
<i>that she could talk me into buying a farm.</i>

37
00:03:35,090 --> 00:03:38,677
<i>I'm 36 years old, I love my family,</i>
<i>I love baseball...</i>

38
00:03:38,802 --> 00:03:41,388
<i>...and I'm about to become a farmer.</i>

39
00:03:42,013 --> 00:03:44,224
<i>But until I heard the voice...</i>

40
00:03:44,766 --> 00:03:48,019
<i>...I'd never done a crazy thing</i>
<i>in my whole life.</i>

41
00:04:25,348 --> 00:04:28,685
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

42
00:04:47,662 --> 00:04:50,999
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

43
00:04:59,841 --> 00:05:01,217
Hey, Annie!

44
00:05:01,760 --> 00:05:04,471
- Annie, what was that?
- What was what?

45
00:05:06,681 --> 00:05:09,142
That voice just now. What was it?

46
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:14,356
We didn't hear anything.

47
00:05:18,360 --> 00:05:19,611
All right.

48
00:05:22,864 --> 00:05:26,201
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

49
00:05:31,623 --> 00:05:34,793
- Okay, you must have heard that!
- Sorry.

50
00:05:35,293 --> 00:05:37,379
Hey, come on in to dinner.

51
00:05:37,879 --> 00:05:39,422
Let's go, pumpkin.

52
00:05:59,150 --> 00:06:01,403
Is there a sound truck on the highway?

53
00:06:01,528 --> 00:06:04,406
Nope. Hey, Karin, dinner's ready!

54
00:06:05,448 --> 00:06:07,826
- Kids with a radio?
- Nope.

55
00:06:08,702 --> 00:06:12,330
- Are you really hearing voices?
- Just one.

56
00:06:13,790 --> 00:06:15,250
What did it say?

57
00:06:16,751 --> 00:06:18,878
"If you build it, he will come."

58
00:06:22,132 --> 00:06:25,760
- If you build what, who will come?
- He didn't say.

59
00:06:27,220 --> 00:06:30,473
- I hate it when that happens.
- Me, too.

60
00:06:44,988 --> 00:06:48,324
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

61
00:07:02,255 --> 00:07:05,133
Build what? What is this?

62
00:07:09,888 --> 00:07:11,639
It's okay, honey.

63
00:07:12,557 --> 00:07:15,101
I'm just talking to the corn field.

64
00:07:19,522 --> 00:07:21,816
<i>Anyway, I was walking</i>
<i>down along the street...</i>

65
00:07:21,941 --> 00:07:24,235
<i>...and I heard this voice saying...</i>

66
00:07:24,361 --> 00:07:26,029
<i>..."Good evening, Mr. Dowd."</i>

67
00:07:26,154 --> 00:07:28,573
<i>Well, I turned around...</i>

68
00:07:29,574 --> 00:07:33,286
<i>...and here was this big six-foot rabbit</i>
<i>leaning up against the lamppost.</i>

69
00:07:37,749 --> 00:07:41,961
- Why did you do that? It was funny.
- Trust me. It's not funny.

70
00:07:42,212 --> 00:07:44,589
The man is sick. Very sick.

71
00:07:44,714 --> 00:07:47,008
Honey, get your book bag. Let's go!

72
00:07:47,133 --> 00:07:51,012
I'll take her today.
I've got some errands to do in town.

73
00:07:51,638 --> 00:07:52,681
Far-out.

74
00:07:57,727 --> 00:08:02,107
- What if the voice calls while you're gone?
- Take a message.

75
00:08:02,816 --> 00:08:04,901
- 'Bye.
- 'Bye.

76
00:08:05,276 --> 00:08:06,319
'Bye.

77
00:08:08,571 --> 00:08:11,116
In all those years, did you ever...

78
00:08:11,658 --> 00:08:14,994
It's just I've heard
that sometimes farmers in the field...

79
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:17,622
They hear things. You know, voices.

80
00:08:17,747 --> 00:08:21,835
- You hearing voices?
- No. It's just I heard some farmers do.

81
00:08:21,960 --> 00:08:26,381
I, of course, don't, so I was wondering
if I was doing something wrong.

82
00:08:28,466 --> 00:08:31,136
Did you ever hear voices out there?

83
00:08:31,261 --> 00:08:34,764
- Who's hearing voices?
- Ray is. Out in the fields.

84
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:36,266
No, I'm not.

85
00:08:37,017 --> 00:08:38,018
I'm...

86
00:08:41,062 --> 00:08:42,605
Noises.

87
00:08:42,897 --> 00:08:44,983
That darned tractor...

88
00:08:45,817 --> 00:08:49,446
I'm just going to get some 3-in-1oil.
That ought to do it.

89
00:08:50,113 --> 00:08:52,866
Nice talking to you.

90
00:09:20,643 --> 00:09:23,438
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

91
00:09:23,772 --> 00:09:26,900
All right, that's it! Who the...

92
00:09:28,276 --> 00:09:30,987
Who are you? What do you want from me?

93
00:09:31,154 --> 00:09:32,197
Son of a bitch.

94
00:09:32,322 --> 00:09:35,658
<i>If you build it, he will come.</i>

95
00:09:37,577 --> 00:09:39,204
If you build it...

96
00:09:47,837 --> 00:09:49,381
If you build it...

97
00:09:56,680 --> 00:09:57,931
...he will come.

98
00:10:26,167 --> 00:10:28,920
You don't suppose
this is like an acid flashback?

99
00:10:30,171 --> 00:10:31,339
I never took acid.

100
00:10:31,423 --> 00:10:34,718
Maybe you will someday.
It's like a flash-forward.

101
00:10:35,593 --> 00:10:37,137
Annie, there's more.

102
00:10:37,220 --> 00:10:39,931
Honey, why don't you eat a little bit?

103
00:10:42,100 --> 00:10:45,186
I think I know what
"If you build it, he will come" means.

104
00:10:45,311 --> 00:10:47,981
Why do I not think
this is such a good thing?

105
00:10:48,815 --> 00:10:52,902
I think it means
that if I build a baseball field out there...

106
00:10:53,862 --> 00:10:57,699
...Shoeless Joe Jackson
will come back and play ball again.

107
00:10:59,451 --> 00:11:00,910
You're kidding?

108
00:11:08,793 --> 00:11:09,794
You're kidding.

109
00:11:12,797 --> 00:11:15,216
Boy, I thought my family was crazy...

110
00:11:15,342 --> 00:11:17,719
...but this is the craziest thing
I've ever heard.

111
00:11:17,844 --> 00:11:19,304
I know it's totally nuts.

112
00:11:19,387 --> 00:11:23,266
- I mean, Shoeless Joe!
- He's dead. Died in '51. He's dead.

113
00:11:23,391 --> 00:11:26,061
- They suspended him, right?
- Right.

114
00:11:26,519 --> 00:11:29,773
- He's still dead?
- As far as I know.

115
00:11:33,443 --> 00:11:35,612
Did you know Babe Ruth copied his swing?

116
00:11:37,739 --> 00:11:39,908
If I did, I've forgotten it.

117
00:11:45,747 --> 00:11:48,708
He was supposed to be
so graceful and agile.

118
00:11:49,417 --> 00:11:52,128
I'd actually like to see him play again...

119
00:11:52,253 --> 00:11:55,507
...to let him play, to right an old wrong.

120
00:11:55,632 --> 00:11:58,301
Wait. Wait a minute.

121
00:12:00,637 --> 00:12:05,016
- Are you actually thinking of doing this?
- No.

122
00:12:06,393 --> 00:12:10,063
I can't think of one good reason
why I should, but...

123
00:12:18,363 --> 00:12:22,158
I'm 36. I have a wife,
a child, and a mortgage...

124
00:12:22,283 --> 00:12:25,161
...and I'm scared to death
I'm turning into my father.

125
00:12:26,621 --> 00:12:28,540
What does he have to do with all this?

126
00:12:30,542 --> 00:12:33,211
I never forgave him for getting old.

127
00:12:36,047 --> 00:12:38,925
By the time he was as old as I am now...

128
00:12:39,426 --> 00:12:41,177
...he was ancient.

129
00:12:43,513 --> 00:12:48,643
He must have had dreams,
but he never did anything about them.

130
00:12:49,894 --> 00:12:53,106
For all I know,
he may have even heard voices, too...

131
00:12:54,441 --> 00:12:57,110
...but he sure didn't listen to them.

132
00:12:57,360 --> 00:13:01,406
The man never did one spontaneous thing
in all the years I knew him.

133
00:13:02,782 --> 00:13:05,952
I'm afraid of that happening to me...

134
00:13:07,620 --> 00:13:10,331
...and something tells me
this may be my last chance...

135
00:13:10,457 --> 00:13:12,417
...to do something about it.

136
00:13:15,628 --> 00:13:17,797
I want to build that field.

137
00:13:20,133 --> 00:13:21,718
Do you think I'm crazy?

138
00:13:22,844 --> 00:13:23,970
Yes.

139
00:13:28,308 --> 00:13:32,896
But I also think
if you really feel you should do this...

140
00:13:35,482 --> 00:13:37,609
...then you should do it.

141
00:13:51,915 --> 00:13:55,794
- What the hell is he doing?
- He's plowing under his corn.

142
00:13:56,336 --> 00:13:57,295
Why?

143
00:14:03,468 --> 00:14:07,097
Ty Cobb called him
the greatest left fielder of all time.

144
00:14:07,347 --> 00:14:11,393
He said his glove
was the place where triples go to die.

145
00:14:11,851 --> 00:14:13,895
- Could he hit?
- Could he hit?

146
00:14:14,020 --> 00:14:16,815
Lifetime average .356,
third highest in history.

147
00:14:17,107 --> 00:14:18,900
Why'd they call him "Shoeless Joe"?

148
00:14:19,901 --> 00:14:21,277
When he was in the minors...

149
00:14:21,403 --> 00:14:24,197
...he bought a new pair of spikes
and hurt his feet.

150
00:14:24,322 --> 00:14:28,076
<i>In the 6th inning, he took them off</i>
<i>and played in his socks.</i>

151
00:14:28,201 --> 00:14:32,622
<i>The players kidded him, called him</i>
<i>"Shoeless Joe" and the name stuck.</i>

152
00:14:33,540 --> 00:14:35,208
He's going to lose his farm.

153
00:14:35,333 --> 00:14:36,501
Damned fool.

154
00:14:36,626 --> 00:14:39,879
<i>Then in 1919,</i>
<i>his team the Chicago White Sox...</i>

155
00:14:40,005 --> 00:14:42,090
<i>...threw the World Series.</i>

156
00:14:42,215 --> 00:14:45,844
- <i>What's "threw"?</i>
- <i>It means they lost it on purpose.</i>

157
00:14:45,969 --> 00:14:48,013
<i>Gamblers paid them to.</i>

158
00:14:48,138 --> 00:14:50,348
<i>Except Shoeless Joe.</i>

159
00:14:50,682 --> 00:14:54,269
<i>He did take their money,</i>
<i>but nobody ever proved he did one thing...</i>

160
00:14:54,394 --> 00:14:55,979
<i>...to lose those games.</i>

161
00:14:57,522 --> 00:15:01,568
If he threw it, how do you explain
that he hit .375 for the Series...

162
00:15:01,693 --> 00:15:03,486
...and committed no errors?

163
00:15:03,611 --> 00:15:04,612
I can't.

164
00:15:04,738 --> 00:15:07,282
Twelve hits including
the Series' only home run...

165
00:15:07,407 --> 00:15:09,701
...and they said he's trying to lose?

166
00:15:09,826 --> 00:15:10,952
It's ridiculous.

167
00:15:11,619 --> 00:15:14,581
<i>The commissioner of baseball</i>
<i>suspended eight of the players...</i>

168
00:15:14,706 --> 00:15:17,709
<i>...including the great Shoeless Joe</i>
<i>Jackson, for life.</i>

169
00:15:17,834 --> 00:15:19,461
<i>What's "suspend"?</i>

170
00:15:20,545 --> 00:15:23,715
<i>It means they never</i>
<i>let him play the game again.</i>

171
00:15:26,551 --> 00:15:28,636
My father said he saw him years later...

172
00:15:28,762 --> 00:15:33,058
...playing under a made-up name
in some 10th-rate league in Carolina.

173
00:15:33,391 --> 00:15:36,686
He'd put on 50 pounds,
and his spring was gone from his step...

174
00:15:36,811 --> 00:15:38,688
...but he could still hit.

175
00:15:39,606 --> 00:15:42,984
Dad used to say
nobody could hit like Shoeless Joe.

176
00:15:44,402 --> 00:15:47,238
I think that's the first time
I've ever seen you smile...

177
00:15:47,364 --> 00:15:49,741
...when you mentioned your father.

178
00:16:03,588 --> 00:16:06,883
I have just created something
totally illogical.

179
00:16:10,512 --> 00:16:12,722
That's what I like about it.

180
00:16:15,225 --> 00:16:17,018
Am I completely nuts?

181
00:16:19,813 --> 00:16:21,481
Not completely.

182
00:16:22,857 --> 00:16:25,318
It's a good baseball field, Ray.

183
00:16:26,236 --> 00:16:28,571
It's kind of pretty, isn't it?

184
00:16:51,511 --> 00:16:52,804
Any sign?

185
00:16:55,640 --> 00:16:58,351
Something's going to happen out there.

186
00:16:59,102 --> 00:17:00,562
I can feel it.

187
00:17:20,290 --> 00:17:23,960
<i>So, for the veteran southpaw,</i>
<i>his summer of woes continues.</i>

188
00:17:24,210 --> 00:17:26,087
<i>That's four straight hits in the inning.</i>

189
00:17:26,212 --> 00:17:28,923
Daddy, what's a "southpaw"?

190
00:17:31,634 --> 00:17:33,845
It means a left-handed pitcher, honey.

191
00:17:35,847 --> 00:17:38,350
- So how bad is it?
- Well.

192
00:17:39,976 --> 00:17:44,064
Considering how much less acreage
we have for corn, I say we'll probably...

193
00:17:45,523 --> 00:17:47,400
...almost break even.

194
00:17:51,571 --> 00:17:54,366
We used up all our savings on that field.

195
00:17:54,991 --> 00:17:57,577
- Daddy?
- Just a minute, Karin.

196
00:18:02,248 --> 00:18:05,293
So what are you saying?
We can't keep the field?

197
00:18:08,129 --> 00:18:10,799
Makes it real hard to keep the farm.

198
00:18:15,470 --> 00:18:17,681
- Daddy.
- In a minute, Karin!

199
00:18:18,932 --> 00:18:21,017
There's a man out there on your lawn.

200
00:19:08,815 --> 00:19:12,360
I'll put up some coffee.
Why don't you go on outside?

201
00:21:10,437 --> 00:21:11,563
Sorry.

202
00:21:15,233 --> 00:21:17,402
I'll get some out there.

203
00:21:48,099 --> 00:21:49,225
Hi.

204
00:21:51,227 --> 00:21:52,479
Ray Kinsella.

205
00:21:54,731 --> 00:21:56,274
Joe Jackson.

206
00:22:24,469 --> 00:22:27,347
I bet it's good to be playing again.

207
00:22:34,145 --> 00:22:36,606
Getting thrown out of baseball...

208
00:22:38,108 --> 00:22:40,944
...was like having part of me amputated.

209
00:22:42,862 --> 00:22:45,156
I've heard that old men wake up...

210
00:22:45,281 --> 00:22:49,369
...and scratch itchy legs
that have been dust for over 50 years.

211
00:22:50,245 --> 00:22:51,705
That was me.

212
00:22:53,289 --> 00:22:55,291
I'd wake up at night...

213
00:22:56,376 --> 00:22:59,504
...with the smell
of the ballpark in my nose...

214
00:23:00,380 --> 00:23:03,383
...with the cool of the grass on my feet...

215
00:23:05,677 --> 00:23:07,762
...the thrill of the grass.

216
00:23:15,520 --> 00:23:16,980
Can you pitch?

217
00:23:18,982 --> 00:23:20,108
Yeah.

218
00:23:21,860 --> 00:23:23,028
Not bad.

219
00:23:39,044 --> 00:23:42,630
- Don't we need a catcher?
- Not if you get it near the plate.

220
00:23:44,674 --> 00:23:45,800
Right.

221
00:23:58,480 --> 00:24:00,940
I'm pitching to Shoeless Joe Jackson.

222
00:24:10,075 --> 00:24:11,076
Nice hit.

223
00:24:26,299 --> 00:24:28,009
See if you can hit my curve.

224
00:24:37,936 --> 00:24:42,107
- You can hit the curve ball.
- Put one right here.

225
00:24:44,317 --> 00:24:45,443
Right.

226
00:24:59,457 --> 00:25:01,418
Right, you're a low-ball hitter.

227
00:25:02,085 --> 00:25:04,295
Man, I did love this game.

228
00:25:06,756 --> 00:25:09,050
I'd have played for food money.

229
00:25:10,301 --> 00:25:14,139
It was the game, the sounds, the smells.

230
00:25:16,349 --> 00:25:20,812
Did you ever hold a ball
or a glove to your face?

231
00:25:21,896 --> 00:25:22,897
Yeah.

232
00:25:23,481 --> 00:25:27,402
I used to love traveling on the trains
from town to town.

